{
  "texts": [
    "Other work exploring 4E approaches to education includes Kraus & Wulf (2022), Macrine & Fugate (2022), Hutto et al. (2022), Videla et al. (2021), Nguyen & Larson (2015), Pouw et al. (2014), Kiefer & Trumpp (2012), Mathias & von Kriegstein (2023).",
    "Very much in line with our picture, Hutto et al (2015) write that: \"You cannot directly teach anyone anything; at best, you can create activities that foster opportunities for a person to construct 5 It also elegantly accounts for the positive affect associated with playful behaviour.",
    "On this account, play feels good because any change in the rate of prediction error over time relative to the agent's expectations manifests in the agent's phenomenology as bodily affect (see, e.g., Van de Cruys 2017; Kiverstein et al. 2017).",
    "This deep linkage between learning and feeling is potentially very helpful for elucidating and weakening the apparent tension between learning (as work) and play (see, e.g., Lillard, 2021).",
    "some targeted knowledge for themselves\" (Hutto et al., 2015. Pp. 377)."
  ]
}